# 🎛️ Real-Time Audio Equalizer

A real-time, multi-band audio equalizer with a live spectrum visualizer, built in Python using `sounddevice`, `numpy`, `scipy`, and a `Tkinter` GUI. Audio captured from your microphone is processed frame-by-frame in the frequency domain and played back through your speakers with adjustable per-band gain — all in real time.

![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.9%2B-blue)
![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-MIT-green)
![Platform](https://img.shields.io/badge/platform-Windows%20%7C%20macOS%20%7C%20Linux-lightgrey)

---

## ✨ Features

- 🎚️ **5-band parametric equalizer** — Sub Bass, Bass, Mid, Upper Mid, Treble (±12 dB per band)
- 🔊 **Real-time processing** — low-latency mic-to-speaker pipeline using FFT-based filtering
- 📈 **Live spectrum visualizer** — logarithmic-scale frequency plot with peak-hold, rendered with `matplotlib` inside the Tkinter window
- 🎼 **Built-in & custom presets** — Flat, Rock, Pop, Jazz, Classical, Voice, plus the ability to save your own as JSON
- 🧹 **Spectral noise reduction** — basic noise-profile subtraction module (`NoiseReducer`)
- 🖥️ **Simple GUI** — start/stop streaming, drag sliders, switch presets, all from one window

---

## 🧠 How It Works

The signal chain for every audio block is:

```
Microphone → Windowing (Hann) → FFT → Noise Reduction → Per-Band Gain → IFFT (Overlap-Add) → Speaker
```

| Component | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| `AudioStream` | Opens the bidirectional mic/speaker stream via `sounddevice` and drives the real-time audio callback |
| `FFTProcessor` | Converts time-domain blocks to the frequency domain (FFT) and reconstructs audio using Overlap-Add (OLA) |
| `Equalizer` | Maps FFT bins to frequency bands and applies independent linear gain per band |
| `NoiseReducer` | Estimates a noise profile and subtracts it from the spectrum |
| `PresetManager` | Loads/saves equalizer presets as JSON files |
| `SpectrumVisualizer` | Renders the live frequency spectrum with peak-hold inside the GUI |
| `EqualizerGUI` | Builds the Tkinter interface and wires all components together |
| `main()` | Entry point — checks for audio devices and launches the GUI |

### DSP Parameter Choices

| Parameter | Value | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Sample rate | 44,100 Hz | CD-quality, covers the full 20 Hz–20 kHz hearing range |
| Block size | 1024 samples (~23 ms) | Low latency while keeping CPU overhead per callback low |
| FFT size | 2048 (zero-padded) | Doubles frequency resolution (~21.5 Hz/bin) for more accurate low-band gain mapping |
| Window | Hann | Suppresses spectral leakage from chopping a continuous signal into blocks |
| Overlap | 50% (hop = 512) | Satisfies the constant-overlap-add (COLA) condition for Hann windows, avoiding amplitude ripple |

### Frequency Bands

| Band | Range |
|---|---|
| Sub Bass | 20 – 60 Hz |
| Bass | 60 – 250 Hz |
| Mid | 250 – 2,000 Hz |
| Upper Mid | 2,000 – 4,000 Hz |
| Treble | 4,000 – 20,000 Hz |

---

## 📦 Requirements

- Python 3.9+
- A working microphone and speakers/headphones
- A system audio backend supported by [PortAudio](http://www.portaudio.com/) (used internally by `sounddevice`)

### Dependencies

```
numpy
scipy
sounddevice
matplotlib
```

> ⚠️ On Linux, you may need to install PortAudio system libraries first:
> ```bash
> sudo apt-get install libportaudio2 portaudio19-dev
> ```

---

## 🚀 Installation

```bash
# Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/<your-repo>.git
cd <your-repo>

# (Recommended) Create a virtual environment
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate      # On Windows: venv\Scripts\activate

# Install dependencies
pip install numpy scipy sounddevice matplotlib
```

---

## ▶️ Usage

Run the application:

```bash
python equalizer.py
```

> Replace `equalizer.py` with the actual filename of the script.

1. Click **▶ Start** to begin streaming audio from your microphone to your speakers.
2. Drag the vertical sliders to boost or cut each frequency band (±12 dB).
3. Watch the live spectrum update in real time.
4. Click a preset button (Flat, Rock, Pop, Jazz, Classical, Voice) to instantly apply a gain profile.
5. Click **Save current status...** to store your current slider settings as a new named preset.
6. Click **■ Stop** to stop the audio stream.

> ⚠️ **Headphones recommended.** Routing live microphone input to speakers can cause audio feedback (a loud howling loop) if the mic picks up the speaker output.

---

## 💾 Presets

Presets are stored as JSON files in a `presets/` folder created automatically next to the script. Built-in presets (`Flat`, `Rock`, `Pop`, `Jazz`, `Classical`, `Voice`) are generated on first run. Each preset file looks like:

```json
{
  "Sub Bass": 4,
  "Bass": 3,
  "Mid": -2,
  "Upper Mid": 2,
  "Treble": 4
}
```

You can edit these files directly or create new ones via the GUI's "Save current status..." button.

